@page "/about"

<PageTitle>About verbasizer</PageTitle>

<div class="about-shell">
    <section class="about-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">About the project</p>
        <h1>From Bowie’s cut-up writing method to a digital Verbasizer.</h1>
        <p class="about-lede">
            This app is inspired by David Bowie’s 1990s Verbasizer workflow: feeding multiple text fragments into a tool,
            reshuffling them, and using the collisions as the spark for new lyrics.
        </p>

        <div class="about-actions">
            <a class="btn btn-primary"
               href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x3IKLMgFaDA"
               target="_blank"
               rel="noreferrer">
                Watch Bowie use the Verbasizer
            </a>
            <a class="btn btn-outline-secondary"
               href="https://www.vice.com/en/article/the-verbasizer-was-david-bowies-1995-lyric-writing-mac-app/"
               target="_blank"
               rel="noreferrer">
                Read more background
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="about-grid">
        <article class="about-card">
            <h2>How it came about</h2>
            <p>
                Bowie had used cut-up writing for years, physically slicing up text and reassembling the fragments to create
                unexpected phrases and images. During the making of <em>Outside</em> in the mid-1990s, he worked with Ty Roberts
                to turn that process into software on a Mac laptop.
            </p>
            <p>
                The result was the Verbasizer: a sentence randomizer that could split several lines into columns and then
                recombine the words into new variations much faster than the old paper-and-scissors method.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="about-card">
            <h2>Why Bowie used it</h2>
            <p>
                Bowie described the output as a “kaleidoscope of meanings” where nouns, verbs, and topics collide in surprising
                ways. He wasn’t using it to replace songwriting; he used it to generate fresh combinations that he could shape
                into lyrics.
            </p>
            <p>
                That digital cut-up approach helped feed the fractured, cinematic language around <em>Outside</em> and connected
                back to the Burroughs / Brion Gysin-inspired techniques he had already explored in earlier decades.
            </p>
        </article>

        <article class="about-card">
            <h2>What this app keeps</h2>
            <p>
                This version keeps the same core idea: combine several source texts, randomize across them, and turn the output
                into new lyric drafts. The difference is that this app also keeps punctuation and sentence flow more intact, so
                the results stay readable while still feeling unstable and strange.
            </p>
        </article>
    </section>

    <section class="sources-card">
        <h2>Source links</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x3IKLMgFaDA" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
                    David Bowie - the Verbasizer (YouTube)
                </a>
            </li>
            <li>
                <a href="https://www.vice.com/en/article/the-verbasizer-was-david-bowies-1995-lyric-writing-mac-app/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">
                    The Verbasizer was David Bowie’s 1995 lyric-writing Mac app (Vice)
                </a>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</div>
